---
import BaseLayout from '../components/layout/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Editorial Activation"
  description="How Editorial Intelligence powers every communication channel through a shared narrative foundation — PR, editorial, thought leadership, customer marketing, sales enablement and events."
>
  <article class="container-site py-20">
    <div class="max-w-2xl">

      <header class="mb-16">
        <p class="t-label mb-6">Activation</p>
        <h1 class="t-display mb-6">From intelligence to activation</h1>
        <p class="t-body text-lg leading-relaxed">
          Most organisations treat research, content and PR as separate activities. Editorial Intelligence connects them into a continuous system where research generates reusable intelligence, intelligence becomes narratives, and narratives power every communication channel.
        </p>
      </header>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- Why activation fragments -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">Why activation usually becomes fragmented</h2>
        <div class="prose-section">
          <p>In most organisations, communication channels operate independently.</p>
          <p>The PR team commissions research for a campaign. The content team produces editorial for a different audience. Thought leadership is written to a separate brief. Customer marketing uses its own evidence base. Sales creates its own messaging.</p>
          <p>Each channel works hard. But because they draw from different sources, speak in different voices and operate on different timelines, they rarely reinforce each other. The result is fragmentation — a lot of activity that does not compound.</p>
          <p>The problem is not the channels. It is the absence of a shared narrative foundation.</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-[var(--color-ink)]">When every team starts from scratch, the organisation cannot build strategic authority over time. It can only produce activity.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- Two models -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">Two models</h2>

        <div class="model-comparison">
          <div class="model model--traditional">
            <p class="model__label">Traditional model</p>
            <ul class="model__steps">
              <li>Commission research</li>
              <li class="model__arrow">{"↓"}</li>
              <li>Extract headline statistic</li>
              <li class="model__arrow">{"↓"}</li>
              <li>Write press release</li>
              <li class="model__arrow">{"↓"}</li>
              <li>Secure coverage</li>
              <li class="model__arrow">{"↓"}</li>
              <li class="model__end">Campaign ends</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="model model--ei">
            <p class="model__label">Editorial Intelligence model</p>
            <ul class="model__steps">
              <li class="model__source-group">
                <span class="model__stage-label">Signals</span>
                <ul class="model__sources">
                  <li>Customer research</li>
                  <li>Customer interviews</li>
                  <li>Events</li>
                  <li>Sales conversations</li>
                  <li>Market trends</li>
                  <li>Operational data</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li class="model__arrow">{"↓"}</li>
              <li class="model__source-group">
                <span class="model__stage-label" style="color: var(--color-accent)">Editorial Intelligence</span>
                <ul class="model__sources">
                  <li>Identify recurring problems</li>
                  <li>Connect evidence</li>
                  <li>Develop narratives</li>
                  <li>Prioritise opportunities</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li class="model__arrow">{"↓"}</li>
              <li class="model__source-group">
                <span class="model__stage-label">Activation</span>
                <ul class="model__sources">
                  <li>PR</li>
                  <li>Editorial</li>
                  <li>Thought leadership</li>
                  <li>Customer marketing</li>
                  <li>Sales enablement</li>
                  <li>Social</li>
                  <li>Events</li>
                  <li>Executive communications</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li class="model__arrow">{"↓"}</li>
              <li class="model__source-group">
                <span class="model__stage-label">Learning</span>
                <ul class="model__sources">
                  <li>Coverage</li>
                  <li>Engagement</li>
                  <li>Customer feedback</li>
                  <li>Sales conversations</li>
                  <li>New market signals</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li class="model__arrow model__arrow--loop">{"↺"} back to Editorial Intelligence</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- Worked example: Hidden Hours -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">Worked example: Hidden Hours</h2>
        <div class="prose-section mb-10">
          <p>Hidden Hours demonstrates what this looks like in practice.</p>
          <p>The research began as practitioner interviews into the operational pressures facing accounting professionals. In a traditional campaign model, it would have become a press release, generated coverage for a quarter, and been filed.</p>
          <p>Instead, one research programme became the foundation for a continuously developing body of work.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="example-comparison">
          <div class="example-col">
            <p class="example-col__label">Traditional campaign</p>
            <ul class="example-steps">
              <li>Commission research</li>
              <li class="example-arrow">{"↓"}</li>
              <li>Find headline statistic</li>
              <li class="example-arrow">{"↓"}</li>
              <li>Write press release</li>
              <li class="example-arrow">{"↓"}</li>
              <li>Secure coverage</li>
              <li class="example-arrow">{"↓"}</li>
              <li class="example-end">Campaign ends</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="example-col example-col--ei">
            <p class="example-col__label">Editorial Intelligence approach</p>
            <p class="example-col__sub">One research programme becomes:</p>
            <ul class="activation-list">
              <li>PR stories</li>
              <li>Editorial series</li>
              <li>Thought leadership</li>
              <li>Customer interviews</li>
              <li>Event discussions</li>
              <li>Executive messaging</li>
              <li>Sales enablement</li>
              <li>Webinars</li>
              <li>LinkedIn content</li>
              <li>Diagnostic tools</li>
              <li>Future research questions</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="insight-block mt-10">
          <p>PR becomes one expression of the intelligence — not the purpose of the research.</p>
          <p>The research was not produced to generate a press release. The press release was one activation of research that was already producing value across multiple channels simultaneously.</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-[var(--color-ink)]">That is the difference between a campaign that ends and a knowledge system that compounds.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- Activation channels -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">Activation channels</h2>
        <div class="prose-section mb-10">
          <p>Each channel below draws from the same narrative foundation. The intelligence does not change. The expression is adapted for the audience and context.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="channel-list">
          {[
            {
              name: 'PR',
              body: 'PR within Editorial Intelligence is not the starting point. It is one activation of an intelligence base that already exists. This changes the nature of PR work significantly: rather than commissioning research to generate a story, the PR team draws from a continuously developing body of evidence. Stories become more specific, more credible and more defensible because they are supported by connected evidence rather than isolated statistics. Coverage becomes a signal rather than the end of the process — new angles, new questions and new audiences feed back into the narrative.',
            },
            {
              name: 'Editorial',
              body: 'Editorial content within an EI system is not produced to fill a calendar. It is produced to develop and deepen the narrative — to add evidence, explore implications, test positions and extend reach into new audiences. Each editorial piece is connected to the narratives and frameworks it supports, making it reusable across channels and discoverable over time rather than consumed once and replaced.',
            },
            {
              name: 'Thought leadership',
              body: 'Thought leadership is most effective when it is specific, evidenced and developed over time rather than asserted. Editorial Intelligence provides the structure for that development: the narrative builds through successive pieces, each adding evidence to a position that becomes more authoritative with each iteration. The executive or practitioner speaking from an EI-developed narrative is not asserting an opinion. They are expressing a position that is supported by research, customer evidence and operational knowledge.',
            },
            {
              name: 'Customer marketing',
              body: 'Customer stories, case studies and testimonials within an EI system are not produced as isolated marketing assets. They are evidence that is indexed against the narratives they support, making it reusable across multiple teams and contexts. The customer story that validates a PR claim is the same story that supports a sales conversation, reinforces an editorial position and contributes to a research finding. It is produced once and used many times.',
            },
            {
              name: 'Sales enablement',
              body: `Sales teams operating with EI-developed narratives have something that generic product positioning cannot provide: a coherent story about the problem the customer faces, built from evidence that the customer recognises. The narrative connects the customer's operational reality to the organisation's understanding of it — which is a more powerful sales tool than a feature comparison or a capability claim.`,
            },
            {
              name: 'Events',
              body: 'Events are one of the richest signal sources in the EI system. Practitioner conversations, panel discussions and audience questions are a continuous stream of evidence about what the market is thinking — which problems are acute, which questions are unresolved, which narratives are landing. Events are not just activation channels. They are signal-gathering opportunities that feed directly back into narrative development.',
            },
          ].map((channel) => (
            <div class="channel">
              <h3 class="channel__name">{channel.name}</h3>
              <p class="channel__body">{channel.body}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- Feedback loops -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">Feedback loops</h2>
        <div class="prose-section">
          <p>Activation is not the end of the cycle. It is the point at which the cycle generates new intelligence.</p>
          <p>Every press release that generates a journalist's question is a signal. Every sales conversation that identifies a new objection is a signal. Every event discussion that surfaces an unexpected concern is a signal. Every customer story that reveals an outcome the organisation hadn't anticipated is a signal.</p>
          <p>In a traditional model, these signals are lost — observed in the moment, noted informally, but not captured in a way that changes the next cycle of work.</p>
          <p>In an EI system, activation is designed to generate signals that feed back into narrative development. Coverage is monitored not just for volume but for the questions it surfaces. Customer conversations are analysed not just for sentiment but for the signals they contain. Events are attended not just to present but to listen.</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-[var(--color-ink)]">The organisation that treats activation as a feedback mechanism becomes smarter with every cycle. The organisation that treats it as an endpoint starts from scratch each time.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- The Activation Layer in EOS -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">The Activation Layer in the EOS</h2>
        <div class="prose-section mb-8">
          <p>The Editorial Intelligence OS includes an Activation Layer — the infrastructure that connects narrative development to communication channels.</p>
          <p>Every activation channel should draw from the same narratives rather than creating independent messaging. The Activation Layer is where that connection is made operational: channel briefs that reference the narrative, evidence libraries that are accessible to all teams, feedback mechanisms that route signals back into the system.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="eos-components">
          {[
            { name: 'Research Library', desc: 'Signal and insight repositories that feed the cycle continuously.' },
            { name: 'Narrative Library', desc: 'Connected narratives, frameworks and editorial assets for discovery and reuse.' },
            { name: 'Workflow Library', desc: 'Repeatable editorial processes that improve with each iteration.' },
            { name: 'AI Agents', desc: 'AI-enabled workflows that accelerate production from connected knowledge.' },
            { name: 'Activation Layer', desc: 'Where intelligence becomes communication. Every channel draws from the same narrative foundation.', highlight: true },
            { name: 'Daily OS', desc: 'The operational rhythm that keeps the cycle running — signal capture, narrative review, activation planning, feedback collection.' },
          ].map((c) => (
            <div class:list={['eos-component', c.highlight && 'eos-component--highlight']}>
              <p class="eos-component__name">{c.name}</p>
              <p class="eos-component__desc">{c.desc}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        <p class="t-small mt-8 italic text-[var(--color-ink-tertiary)]">
          The Activation Layer is documented as part of the <a href="/experiments/editorial-intelligence-os" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] no-underline hover:underline">Editorial Intelligence OS experiment</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- Closing -->
      <section class="mb-8">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">Editorial Intelligence is not a content process</h2>
        <div class="prose-section">
          <p>The purpose of introducing activation into the Editorial Intelligence framework is not to expand the scope of what Editorial Intelligence claims to do.</p>
          <p>It is to clarify what Editorial Intelligence is.</p>
          <p>Editorial Intelligence is not a methodology for producing better content. It is an operating model for building organisational knowledge into a strategic asset that powers every communication channel — over time, with compounding effect.</p>
          <p>PR, thought leadership, editorial, customer marketing and sales enablement are not separate disciplines that happen to be connected by a shared narrative. They are different expressions of the same intelligence — the same research, the same customer evidence, the same accumulated understanding of the markets the organisation serves.</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-[var(--color-ink)]">Editorial Intelligence is the operating model that makes that possible.</p>
          <p>Not by adding process.</p>
          <p>By connecting what already exists.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="nav-links">
        <a href="/intelligence" class="nav-link">← Editorial Intelligence</a>
        <a href="/cycle" class="nav-link">The Cycle →</a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .prose-section p {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .prose-section p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }

  /* Two-model comparison */
  .model-comparison {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 2rem;
  }
  @media (min-width: 640px) {
    .model-comparison { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
  }

  .model {
    padding: 1.5rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-rule, #2c2920);
    border-radius: 4px;
    background: var(--color-surface-secondary);
  }
  .model--ei {
    border-top: 2px solid var(--color-accent);
  }

  .model__label {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.625rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary);
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .model__steps {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.375rem;
  }

  .model__steps li {
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  .model__arrow {
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary) !important;
    font-size: 0.75rem !important;
    padding-left: 0.25rem;
  }

  .model__arrow--loop {
    color: var(--color-accent) !important;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.625rem !important;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    margin-top: 0.25rem;
  }

  .model__end {
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary) !important;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .model__source-group {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.375rem;
  }

  .model__stage-label {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.6rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-ink);
  }

  .model__sources {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0 0 0 0.75rem;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.2rem;
    border-left: 1px solid var(--color-rule);
    padding-left: 0.75rem;
  }

  .model__sources li {
    font-size: 0.75rem !important;
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary) !important;
  }

  /* Worked example comparison */
  .example-comparison {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 1.5rem;
  }
  @media (min-width: 640px) {
    .example-comparison { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
  }

  .example-col {
    padding: 1.5rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-rule, #2c2920);
    border-radius: 4px;
    background: var(--color-surface-secondary);
  }

  .example-col--ei {
    border-top: 2px solid var(--color-accent);
  }

  .example-col__label {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.625rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .example-col__sub {
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
    margin-bottom: 0.875rem;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .example-steps {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.375rem;
  }

  .example-steps li {
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
  }

  .example-arrow {
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary) !important;
    font-size: 0.75rem !important;
    padding-left: 0.25rem;
  }

  .example-end {
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary) !important;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .activation-list {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.375rem;
  }

  .activation-list li {
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
    padding-left: 0.875rem;
    position: relative;
  }

  .activation-list li::before {
    content: '→';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-size: 0.7rem;
  }

  .insight-block {
    padding: 1.5rem;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--color-accent);
    background: var(--color-surface-secondary);
    border-radius: 0 4px 4px 0;
  }

  .insight-block p {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .insight-block p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }

  /* Activation channels */
  .channel-list {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0;
  }

  .channel {
    padding: 1.5rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-rule, #2c2920);
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }

  @media (min-width: 640px) {
    .channel {
      grid-template-columns: 10rem 1fr;
      gap: 2rem;
    }
  }

  .channel:first-child { padding-top: 0; }
  .channel:last-child { border-bottom: none; padding-bottom: 0; }

  .channel__name {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1rem;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    padding-top: 0.125rem;
  }

  .channel__body {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
  }

  /* EOS components */
  .eos-components {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }

  @media (min-width: 640px) {
    .eos-components { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
  }

  .eos-component {
    padding: 1.25rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-surface-tertiary);
    border-radius: 4px;
    background: var(--color-surface-secondary);
  }

  .eos-component--highlight {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    border-left: 2px solid var(--color-accent);
  }

  .eos-component__name {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    margin-bottom: 0.375rem;
  }

  .eos-component--highlight .eos-component__name {
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .eos-component__desc {
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary);
  }

  /* Nav links */
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-rule, #2c2920);
    margin-top: 2rem;
  }

  .nav-link {
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary);
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: color 0.15s;
  }

  .nav-link:hover { color: var(--color-accent); }
</style>
